evere LD as well as a new dx of ASD and an auditory processing disorder. &#10;The school reports for his statement said he struggles to access any part of the curriculum and needs constant support to understand even the basics. &#10;Yet they send him home with Yr 2 literacy and numeracy homework asking him to use metaphors, number patterns, fill in missing verbs etc etc etc. &#10;I dont know that much about education but I am willing to bet if he COULD do those things he wouldnt be classed as having severe SEN would he? &#10;Or do they just think his disability is only evident in school and when he gets home he grows a new head? &#10;(bitter and twisted - me)"/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="946" language="en" documentId="4921" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Becki J" date="06-04-10 16:51" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://www.netmums.com/coffeehouse/general-coffeehouse-chat-514/news-current-affairs-topical-discussion-12/405944-special-needs-children-mainstream-schools-all.html" topic="mainstreaming" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="4921" notes="" title="Special Needs children in Mainstream Schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="13"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="14" end="134"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="135" end="372"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="373" end="523"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="524" end="669"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="59" sofa="1" begin="670" end="813"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="63" sofa="1" begin="814" end="920"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="67" sofa="1" begin="921" end="946"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55 59 63 67"/></xmi:XMI>